  "name": "Analyzing unread email subscriptions",
  "summary": "**Conversation Overview**\n\nThe person asked Claude to analyze their Gmail inbox to identify which subscription emails typically go unread, with a request to use any helpful connector and to create something visual or interactive to review together. Claude connected to Gmail and searched for unread emails matching newsletter and subscription patterns, retrieving the 100 most recent results for analysis.\n\nClaude built an interactive dashboard displaying key metrics: 100+ unread emails from 28 unique senders, categorized into newsletters, promotions, system notifications, and Korean-language content. The dashboard included a bar chart by category, a filterable sender list with volume bars, verdict tags (unsubscribe / keep / review), and per-sender \"ask вЖЧ\" buttons for follow-up questions. Claude provided reasoning for each verdict based on relevance to the person's apparent focus areas, including AI/AX work, physical AI and robotics, data science, HR analytics, and organizational research.\n\nNotable findings included CoolDeep AI as the highest-volume sender at 12 emails with repetitive clickbait-style subjects, and a pattern of GitHub Actions workflow failure notifications (5 emails) for a repo called `my_team` running a \"Daily Thought Processing\" job вАФ flagged as a system issue requiring action rather than a subscription to manage. Eleven senders were recommended for unsubscribing, including Uber/Uber Eats, FOX One, Coursera, GPT Workspace, Medium Newsletter, Sider AI, and monday.com.\n\n**Tool Knowledge**\n\nGmail search using `is:unread (unsubscribe OR newsletter OR \"no-reply\" OR noreply)` with `maxResults: 100` effectively surfaced subscription-type unread mail in bulk. This query pattern combining read-state filtering with common subscription signal terms worked well for inbox auditing. The person's Gmail contains a mix of English and Korean-language newsletters, so future searches may benefit from including Korean sender domains or subject-line terms to ensure full coverage of that segment.",
